p-size - the winning strategy is to play in such a heap, reducing that heap to the nim-sum of its original size with X. In the example above, taking the nim-sum of the sizes is . The nim-sums of the heap sizes A=3, B=4, and C=5 with X=2 are\nThe only heap that is reduced is heap A, so the winning move is to reduce the size of heap A to 1 (by removing two objects).", "qas": []}, {"context": "As a particular simple case, if there are only two heaps left, the strategy is to reduce the number of objects in the bigger heap to make the heaps equal. After that, no matter what move your opponent makes, you can make the same move on the other heap, guaranteeing that you take the last object.", "qas": []}, {"context": "When played as a mis\u00e8re game, Nim strategy is different only when the normal play move would leave only heaps of size one. In that case, the correct move is to leave an odd number of heaps of size one (in normal play, the correct move would be to leave an even number of such heaps).", "qas": []}, {"context": "In a mis\u00e8re game with heaps of sizes three, four and five, the strategy would be applied like this:", "qas": []}, {"context": "The previous strategy for a mis\u00e8re game can be easily implemented (for example in Python, below).", "qas": []}, {"context": "The soundness of the optimal strategy described above was demonstrated by C. Bouton.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Theorem. In a normal Nim game, the player making the first move has a winning strategy if and only if the nim-sum of the sizes of the heaps is nonzero. Otherwise, the second player has a winning strategy.", "qas": []}, {"context": "\"Proof:\" Notice that the nim-sum (\u2295) obeys the usual associative and commutative laws of addition (+) and also satisfies an additional property, \"x\"\u00a0\u2295\u00a0\"x\"\u00a0=\u00a00.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Let \"x\",\u00a0...,\u00a0\"x\" be the sizes of the heaps before a move, and \"y\",\u00a0...,\u00a0\"y\" the corresponding sizes after a