, 0, 0)"}]}, {"context": "\u00c9variste Galois was the first to realize the importance of the existence of normal subgroups.", "qas": []}, {"context": "A subgroup of a group is called a normal subgroup if it is invariant under conjugation; that is, the conjugation of an element of by an element of is always in . The usual notation for this relation is formula_1, and the definition may be written in symbols as", "qas": []}, {"context": "For any subgroup, the following conditions are equivalent to normality. Therefore, any one of them may be taken as the definition:", "qas": []}, {"context": "The last condition accounts for some of the importance of normal subgroups; they are a way to internally classify all homomorphisms defined on a group. For example, a non-identity finite group is simple if and only if it is isomorphic to all of its non-identity homomorphic images, a finite group is perfect if and only if it has no normal subgroups of prime index, and a group is imperfect if and only if the derived subgroup is not supplemented by any proper normal subgroup.", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "The normal subgroups of a group, , form a lattice under subset inclusion with least element, , and greatest element, . Given two normal subgroups, and , in , meet is defined as\nand join is defined as \nThe lattice is complete and modular.", "qas": []}, {"context": "If is a normal subgroup, we can define a multiplication on cosets as follows:", "qas": []}, {"context": "With this operation, the set of cosets is itself a group, called the quotient group and denoted . There is a natural homomorphism, given by . The image consists only of the identity element of , the coset .", "qas": []}, {"context": "In general, a group homomorphism, sends subgroups of to subgroups of . Also, the preimage of any subgroup of is a subgroup of . We call the preimage of the trivial group in the kernel of the homomorphism and denote it by . As it turns out, the kernel is always no