up to 96 sprites per scanline for a total of 380 sprites on the screen at a time. Unlike most other video game consoles of its time, the Neo Geo does not use scrolling tilemap background layers. Instead, it has a single non-scrolling tilemap layer called the fix layer, while any scrolling layers rely exclusively on drawing sprites to create the scrolling backgrounds (like the Sega Y Board). By laying multiple sprites side by side, the system can simulate a tilemap background layer. The Neo Geo sprite system represents a step between conventional sprites and tilemaps.", "qas": []}, {"context": "\nThe onboard Yamaha YM2610 sound chip gives the system 15 channels of sound.", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "\nThe Neo Geo is the first home game console to feature a removable memory card for saved games.", "qas": []}, {"context": "The GameTap subscription service has included a Neo Geo emulator and a small library of Neo Geo games. In 2007 Nintendo announced that Neo Geo games would appear on the Wii's Virtual Console, starting with \"\", \"Art of Fighting\", and \"World Heroes\". Neo Geo games were released through Xbox Live Arcade and PlayStation Network, including \"Fatal Fury Special\", \"Samurai Shodown II\", \"Metal Slug 3\", \"\" and \"The King of Fighters '98\". Many Neo Geo games were released on the PlayStation 4, Xbox One, and Nintendo Switch through the Arcade Collection Archives (ACA) service.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Homebrew activity began after the console's discontinuation, both by noncommercial hobbyists and commercially.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Neo Geo has a community of collectors. Because of the limited production runs received by cartridges amongst the sizable available arcade library, some of the rarest Neo Geo games can sell for well over $1,000. The most valuable game is the European AES version of \"Kizuna Encounter\". The MVS market provides a cheaper alternative t